  "prompt": "Can Xenon make Xenon tetrafluoride? If not, why?",
  "response": "Yes, Xenon can make Xenon tetrafluoride (XeF\u2084).\n\nThe noble gases were once thought to be completely inert, incapable of forming chemical bonds. However, in 1962, Neil Bartlett synthesized xenon hexafluoroplatinate, Xe\u207a[PtF\u2086]\u207b, demonstrating that noble gases could indeed participate in chemical reactions.\n\nFollowing this discovery, it was soon realized that Xenon could react directly with fluorine to form several fluorides, including XeF\u2082, XeF\u2084, and XeF\u2086.\n\nThe formation of Xenon tetrafluoride (XeF\u2084) typically requires heating a mixture of Xenon and Fluorine gas to a high temperature (around 400\u00b0C) and often requires a nickel or other suitable metal container to act as a catalyst.  The stoichiometry of the reactants (Xe:F\u2082) influences the product distribution. Excess fluorine favors higher fluorides.\n\n**Therefore, the statement that Xenon cannot make Xenon tetrafluoride is incorrect.**\n",
